Hi @JaeseokWoo, thanks for your time! Unfortunally, this can break a lot of existing code...

First of all, with the amount of information that you provided, [`403 Forbidden`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Status/403) codes does not make any sense with the [`Accept-Encondig`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Accept-Encoding) header, because `403 Forbidden` is should be used to authorization / authentication logic.

Even if, for some unknown reason, the web server returns `403 Forbidden` when there's no `Accept-Encoding` provided, this cannot be statically hard-coded in the axios code. Because you will be forcing all, literally all current axios users, to support all of these 3 encodings (by default) and handle it's encoded responses.

If that helps, you can create you own `AxiosInstance` with some default settings to reduce the amount of duplicated code:

```js
const axios = require('axios');

axios.create({
  headers: {
    'content-encoding': 'gzip, deflate, br'
  }
});

instance.get('url').then(doSomeStuff);
```

