@jimmywarting So far it doesn't make much sense to deprecate the `form-data` package. Both implementations work well with simple data, while native FormData API doesn't have `File` interface to represent the FileSystem Blob (`form-data` supports streams as a payload)
In addition, it seems Blob implementations don't support memory-efficient data streaming, since they store all chunks in RAM. 
If this is true, then it casts doubt on the possibility of using this API as the main one for a server environment where huge files can be transferred in a multi-threaded environment.

> while native FormData API doesn't have File interface to represent the FileSystem Blob

well, That's true. but all three spec compliant FormData impl. that I know of supports Blob/File look-a-like items. 

if you use something like [fetch-blob](https://github.com/node-fetch/fetch-blob) then you can create Blob/File like objects backed up by the filesystem so that nothings needs to be kept in RAM. 
`node-fetch` and `got` both deprecated `form-data` also b/c it wasn't spec compatible.

```js
// The default export is sync and use fs.stat to retrieve size & last modified as a blob
import blobFromSync from 'fetch-blob/from.js'
import { File, Blob, blobFrom, blobFromSync, fileFrom, fileFromSync } from 'fetch-blob/from.js'

const fsFile = fileFromSync('./2-GiB-file.bin', 'application/octet-stream')
const fsBlob = await blobFrom('./2-GiB-file.mp4')

// Not a 4 GiB memory snapshot, just holds references
// points to where data is located on the disk
const blob = new Blob([fsFile, fsBlob, 'memory', new Uint8Array(10)])
console.log(blob.size) // ~4 GiB
```
undici (NodeJS) FormData, as well as [formdata-polyfill](https://www.npmjs.com/package/formdata-polyfill) and [formdata-node](https://www.npmjs.com/package/formdata-node) supports Blob / File look-a-like items. 

You can even do something like:
```js
const form = new FormData()

// You can use file-shaped or blob-shaped objects as FormData value instead of creating separate class
form.set("stream", {
  type: "text/plain",
  name: "file.txt",
  size: 1024,
  [Symbol.toStringTag]: "File",
  stream() {
    return getStreamFromSomewhere()
  }
})
```

This is how both `node-fetch` and `got` recommends adding files to FormData. 

(formdata-node comes with it's own way of getting a File like object - mostly copied from fetch-blob)
```js
import {fileFromPath} from 'formdata-node/file-from-path'
```
the only thing this dose is stat-ing the file for getting the file name, size & last modified date. nothing is really held in memory. and nothing is read until you actually start piping the formdata to the network request. 

--- 

`form-data` haven't been updated in ages and still lacks proper FormData methods such as get(), delete(), has(), entries() and much more.

And something that you really expect to get out of doing something like `request.formData().then(...)` is to get out a spec'ed `FormData` back so that you can iterate over all fields to get all the values. 
But i know that you don't currently support parsing a response or a request into a `FormData` yet.

But if that's something you would add support for then you better have a spec compatible FormData.

with `node-fetch` and built in `fetch` you can basically do something like:

```js
app.post('/upload', (req, res) => {
  new Response(req, { headers: req.headers }).formData().then(fd => {
    const file = fd.get('file')
    console.log(file.size)
    file.stream().pipeTo(dest)
  })
})
```

no extra busboy parser or anything needed at all...

