Oh, you're almost right, it turns out Webpack uses `node-libs-browser` which pulls in shim libraries like `stream-http`,  `http-browserify`, and `zlib-browserify`.

So yes, maybe Axios seems big to other people because they are pulling in those shim libraries.

I wasn't expecting any shim libraries to be involved because I'm used to code that dynamically checks for what's supported/available, something along the lines of:

```js
if (typeof XMLHTTPRequest === "function") {
   ...
} else {
   const http = await import("http");
   ...
}
```

(That kind of code also allows for separate browser and node builds, but the penalty for having a single build is much less.)

> But if we consider this acceptable, then nothing has changed since version 1.2.1 

Nothing changed in a hypothetical world where all Node JS imports are shimmed and the shims works exactly as the real imports.  What I meant is that, in reality, Webpack builds used to work, but now they don't.

You can of course say that it's not an Axios issue, and that you never intended to support this kind of build.

But the first thing that changed was that 1.2.1 introduced references to `zlib.constants` which work with Node but not with the shim:

```js
const zlibOptions = {
  flush: zlib.constants.Z_SYNC_FLUSH,
  finishFlush: zlib.constants.Z_SYNC_FLUSH
};
```

(For some reason the shim defines `zlib.Z_SYNC_FLUSH` not `zlib.constants.Z_SYNC_FLUSH`.)

The second thing that changed (in this commit) is that you  `import { TextEncoder } from "util"` instead of accessing it as a global.   On browsers, the global works but the import doesn't, because Webpack isn't shimming that import.

